
Elasticity modelling is about understanding how sensitive customer behaviour is to price changes.

🧠 ✅ Simple definition
	Elasticity = how much demand (or conversion) changes when price changes

📊 1. The key idea (very intuitive)
If you increase price:
	• Do customers still buy? → low elasticity
	• Do they drop off quickly? → high elasticity

🔢 2. Basic formula (good to know)

"Price Elasticity"=(%" change in demand" )/(%" change in price" )
 

✅ Interpretation:
Elasticity value	Meaning
~0	Demand barely changes → insensitive
-1	1% ↑ price → 1% ↓ demand
< -1	Very sensitive (elastic)
> -1	Less sensitive (inelastic)

🚗 3. In pricing (your context)
You’re modelling something like:

"Conversion probability"=f("price" ⓜ,"customer features" )
 

✅ What you’re trying to answer:
	• If price ↑ 10%, how much will: 
		○ Conversion ↓ ?
	• Is this group: 
		○ Price sensitive?
		○ Loyal / less sensitive?

🔍 4. Practical example (motor insurance)
Customer group	Price change	Conversion change	Interpretation
Young drivers	+10%	-15%	Highly price sensitive
Older drivers	+10%	-3%	Less sensitive
👉 Insight:
	• Charge higher margins to low-elasticity groups
	• Be competitive for high-elasticity groups

🧠 5. How you actually model it (technical)
✅ A. Logistic regression (common)

"logit"(P("convert" ))=β_0+β_1⋅"price"+…
 
	• Coefficient on price → elasticity signal

✅ B. More advanced approaches
	• Gradient boosting (non-linear elasticity)
	• Interaction terms: 
		○ Price × age
		○ Price × region

✅ C. Output you care about:
	• Conversion curve: 
		○ Price vs probability of purchase

🎯 6. Why elasticity modelling matters
✅ A. Profit optimisation
Balance:
	• Higher prices → more margin
	• Lower prices → more customers
Goal:

"Maximise profit"="price"×"conversion"
 

✅ B. Personalised pricing
Different customers:
	• Different willingness to pay

✅ C. Competitive strategy
	• Avoid overpricing sensitive segments
	• Extract value from insensitive ones

⚖️ 7. Link to regulation (important!)
Elasticity modelling introduces risks:
⚠️ Fairness
	• Different prices for different people
	• Must be: 
		○ Risk-based
		○ Justifiable

⚠️ Transparency
	• Must explain: 
		○ Why price differs

⚠️ GDPR / profiling
	• This is effectively: 
		○ Behavioural prediction
	• Needs: 
		○ Governance
		○ Explainability

🎤 💬 Interview-ready answer
	Elasticity modelling is used to estimate how sensitive customer demand or conversion is to changes in price. In practice, it involves modelling the relationship between price and the probability of purchase, often using regression or machine learning techniques. This allows us to understand how different customer segments respond to pricing changes and optimise pricing strategies to balance competitiveness and profitability. It’s particularly important in regulated environments to ensure that pricing differences remain fair, explainable, and justified.

🚀 Bonus (very strong insight)
	“Elasticity is often heterogeneous—different segments have different sensitivities—so modelling interactions between price and customer characteristics is key.”

🎯 One-liner to remember
	Elasticity modelling tells you how far you can move price before customers walk away.

