🧩 📊 Worked Example: Elasticity Modelling
🎯 Scenario
You’re pricing a motor insurance product.
You test different prices and observe:
Price (£)	Conversion Rate (%)
500	20%
550	17%
600	14%
650	11%

🔹 Step 1: Calculate elasticity
We’ll calculate elasticity between two points.
Example: £500 → £550
✅ Step A: % change in price

(550−500)/500=0.10=10%
 

✅ Step B: % change in conversion

(17−20)/20=−0.15=−15%
 

✅ Step C: Elasticity

"Elasticity"=(−15%)/(10%)=−1.5
 

✅ Interpretation:
	• Elasticity = -1.5
	• Demand is elastic
👉 A 1% increase in price → 1.5% drop in conversion
👉 Customers are price sensitive

🔹 Step 2: Do this across segments (very important)
Suppose:
Segment A (young drivers)
Price	Conversion
500	25%
550	18%
Elasticity:

(−28%)/(10%)=−2.8
 
👉 Very elastic (highly price sensitive)

Segment B (older drivers)
Price	Conversion
500	15%
550	14%
Elasticity:

(−6.7%)/(10%)=−0.67
 
👉 Inelastic (less price sensitive)

🔹 Step 3: Convert to business insight
Segment	Elasticity	Strategy
Young drivers	-2.8	Keep prices competitive
Older drivers	-0.67	Can increase prices

🔹 Step 4: Profit optimisation (this is the real goal)
Let’s calculate expected revenue:

"Revenue"="Price"×"Conversion"
 

At £500:

500×20%=100
 
At £550:

550×17%=93.5
 
At £600:

600×14%=84
 

✅ Insight:
	• Revenue decreases as price increases 👉 This means:
	• You are in a high elasticity region
	• Raising price hurts overall revenue

🔹 Step 5: What if elasticity is low?
Suppose:
Price	Conversion
500	20%
550	19%
Revenue:
	• £500 → 100
	• £550 → 104.5
👉 Revenue increased
✅ Insight:
	• Customers are insensitive
	• You can increase prices profitably

🔹 Step 6: How this looks in modelling (real-world)
Instead of tables, you estimate:

P("convert" )=1/(1+e^(−(β_0+β_1⋅"price" ) ) )
 
	• If β₁ is strongly negative → high elasticity
	• If β₁ is small → low elasticity

🔥 🎯 Interview-level insight
✅ Key point to say:
	“Elasticity is not constant—it varies by segment and price level, so the goal is to model it dynamically rather than rely on a single estimate.”

💬 Strong interview answer
	For example, if increasing price by 10% leads to a 15% drop in conversion, elasticity would be -1.5, indicating high price sensitivity. In this case, increasing prices would likely reduce overall revenue. However, for less sensitive segments, where conversion drops less than price increases, there is an opportunity to increase profitability. In practice, I would model elasticity using regression techniques and apply it at a segment level to optimise pricing decisions.

🚀 Final takeaway
	Elasticity tells you whether increasing prices makes you more money—or loses you money.

