🧠 🎯 What is Price Optimisation?
	Price optimisation = choosing the price that maximises an objective (usually profit), using elasticity models.

🔑 1. The core idea
You’re balancing two opposing forces:
	• Higher price → ✅ more margin per policy
	• Higher price → ❌ fewer customers (lower conversion)

✅ Objective:

"Maximise Profit"
 

🔢 2. The fundamental formula
✅ Profit per customer:

"Profit"=("Price" −"Cost" )×P("conversion" )
 
Where:
	• Price = premium you charge
	• Cost = expected claims + expenses
	• P("conversion" )  = from elasticity model

🧩 3. Simple worked example
🎯 Given:
	• Expected cost = £400
	• Conversion model:
	Price	Conversion
	500	20%
	550	17%
	600	14%

✅ Step 1: Calculate profit
Price = £500

(500−400)×20%=100×0.2=20
 

Price = £550

(550−400)×17%=150×0.17=25.5
 

Price = £600

(600−400)×14%=200×0.14=28
 

✅ Result:
Price	Profit
500	20
550	25.5
600	28 (optimal)

🎯 Key insight:
Even though conversion drops: ➡ higher margin outweighs it → higher profit

⚙️ 4. How optimisation works in practice
Instead of testing a few prices, you:
✅ Step A: Build two models
1. Risk model

"Expected Cost"=f(X)
 
2. Demand (elasticity) model

P("conversion" )=f("price" ⓜ,X)
 

✅ Step B: Optimise price per customer
For each customer:

"Optimal Price"=arg⁡(max⁡ )┬p  (p−"cost" )×P("conversion" )
 

✅ Step C: Solve numerically
	• Try many candidate prices
	• Pick the one with highest profit
👉 This is often done via:
	• Grid search
	• Gradient-based optimisation

🧠 5. Advanced version (what strong candidates mention)
✅ A. Continuous optimisation
Instead of discrete prices:

(max⁡ )┬p (p−c)⋅σ(β_0+β_1 p+…" " )
 
Where:
	• σ = logistic function

✅ B. Segment-level optimisation
Different customers → different optimal prices
👉 Example:
	• Young drivers → lower optimal price
	• Loyal customers → higher optimal price

✅ C. Constraints (VERY important)
Real-world optimisation is constrained:
🔹 Business constraints:
	• Min / max price
	• Competitor positioning

🔹 Regulatory constraints:
	• Fairness (no discrimination)
	• Transparency
	• Avoid excessive price differences

🔹 Operational constraints:
	• Smooth pricing (avoid big jumps)

👉 So actual problem becomes:

(max⁡ )┬p "Profit" "s.t. constraints"
 

⚖️ 6. Key risks (this is where you stand out)
⚠️ A. Fairness
	• Charging different prices based on behaviour
	• Risk of indirect discrimination

⚠️ B. Overfitting elasticity
	• Wrong elasticity → wrong pricing

⚠️ C. Customer trust
	• Highly personalised prices may feel unfair

⚠️ D. Regulatory scrutiny (UK specifically)
	• FCA Consumer Duty
	• Pricing must be: 
		○ Fair
		○ Justifiable

🧠 7. GLM vs ML in optimisation (tie-in)
	• GLM: 
		○ Simpler elasticity → stable optimisation
	• ML: 
		○ More accurate demand → better optimisation
		○ BUT: 
			§ Harder to control
			§ Higher fairness risk

🎤 💬 Interview-ready answer
⭐ “How does price optimisation work?”
	Price optimisation involves combining a risk model, which estimates expected cost, with a demand or elasticity model, which estimates the probability of conversion as a function of price. The objective is typically to maximise expected profit, calculated as margin multiplied by conversion probability.
	In practice, this involves evaluating different price points for each customer and selecting the price that maximises profit, often subject to constraints such as regulatory requirements, fairness considerations, and business rules. The key challenge is balancing profitability with customer behaviour, while ensuring pricing remains explainable and compliant.

🔥 💡 “Top 5% candidate” insight
	“Optimisation is only as good as the elasticity model—if demand is misestimated, the pricing strategy can be systematically wrong.”

🎯 One-line takeaway
	Price optimisation finds the price where higher margins stop being worth the lost customers.

