🧩 ⚖️ CHALLENGE SCENARIO
❓ Question:
	Your price optimisation model suggests charging significantly higher premiums to a group of customers (e.g. those in certain postcodes or with lower price sensitivity).
	This maximises profit, but there are concerns it may be unfair or discriminatory.
	What would you do?

✅ ✅ What interviewers are testing
They want to see if you can:
	• Balance profit vs fairness ✅
	• Understand regulatory expectations (GDPR, FCA Consumer Duty) ✅
	• Show good judgement, not just technical accuracy ✅

🧠 ✅ STRUCTURED APPROACH
	1. Understand the issue → 2. Diagnose the cause → 3. Assess risk → 4. Take action → 5. Govern going forward

✅ 🧠 MODEL ANSWER (STEP-BY-STEP)
🔹 1. Understand the pricing difference
	“First, I would quantify and understand the pricing differences.”
	• Which groups are affected?
	• How large are the differences?
	• Are they: 
		○ Risk-driven?
		○ Behaviour-driven (elasticity)?
👉 Key distinction:
	• Risk-based pricing ✅ usually acceptable
	• Behavioural pricing ⚠️ more sensitive

🔹 2. Diagnose the root cause (VERY important)
A. Risk vs elasticity
	• Is the higher price due to: 
		○ Higher expected claims? ✅
		○ Lower price sensitivity? ⚠️
👉 If it’s purely due to elasticity:
	• This is price discrimination based on behaviour

B. Proxy variables
	• Are variables (e.g. postcode) acting as proxies for: 
		○ Income
		○ Ethnicity
👉 This introduces:
	• Indirect discrimination risk

C. Model behaviour
	• Is ML model: 
		○ Amplifying small differences?
		○ Creating unstable outputs?

🔹 3. Assess regulatory & fairness risks
	“I would evaluate whether the outcome is fair and defensible.”
Key questions:
	• Can we justify the price difference?
	• Would this be: 
		○ Acceptable to regulators?
		○ Explainable to customers?

⚠️ Potential concerns:
	• Vulnerable customers overcharged
	• Certain regions consistently penalised
	• Lack of transparency

🔹 4. Decide on action (THIS is the hardest part)
✅ Option 1: Adjust pricing model (most common)
Actions:
	• Introduce constraints: 
		○ Cap price differences
	• Reduce weight of elasticity component
	• Remove or adjust proxy variables
👉 Goal:
	• Balance fairness + profitability

✅ Option 2: Segment-level controls
	• Apply pricing rules: 
		○ Limit differences between groups
	• Ensure: 
		○ No extreme outliers

✅ Option 3: Hybrid approach (very strong answer)
	Keep optimisation but constrain it
Example:

max⁡"Profit"   "s.t. fairness constraints"
 

Fairness constraints could include:
	• Max % difference between similar risks
	• No systematic disadvantage to a group

🔹 5. Strengthen governance
	“I would also put controls in place to prevent recurrence.”
	• Regular fairness testing
	• Monitoring: 
		○ Price distribution by segment
	• Clear documentation: 
		○ Why differences exist

⚖️ ✅ Key trade-off (important to articulate)
Goal	Risk
Maximise profit	May create unfair outcomes
Ensure fairness	May reduce profitability
👉 Strong candidates say:
	“The goal is not to maximise profit at all costs, but to optimise within acceptable fairness and regulatory boundaries.”

🎤 💬 TOP-TIER INTERVIEW ANSWER
	I would first analyse the drivers of the pricing differences to determine whether they are primarily risk-based or driven by elasticity and behavioural factors. If the differences are driven by elasticity alone, I would consider this a higher regulatory risk, particularly if certain groups are systematically disadvantaged.
	I would then assess whether the pricing is fair, explainable, and justifiable, considering potential proxy variables such as postcode that may introduce indirect bias.
	If concerns exist, I would adjust the optimisation approach by introducing constraints, such as limiting price differences between similar risk profiles or reducing reliance on behavioural factors.
	Finally, I would strengthen governance by implementing fairness monitoring, documenting model decisions, and ensuring that pricing outcomes remain aligned with regulatory expectations and customer fairness principles.

🔥 💡 “Top 5% candidate” insights
You can add:
✅
	“Not all profit is good profit—if it’s not sustainable from a regulatory or reputational perspective, it can create long-term risk.”
✅
	“Fairness should be built into the optimisation itself, not just checked after.”

🎯 One-line takeaway
	The best pricing strategy maximises profit within fairness and regulatory constraints—not beyond them.
